    "narrative": "The Austin Waves offense faces a mixed slate today, but the clear anchor for the lineup is **Gunnar Henderson**, who earns our highest grade at 83.29. Facing Kelly, his leadoff positioning combined with a significant +16% park factor and an 87% steal-probability against a slow-delivery pitcher makes him a locked-in elite play. **Luis Garc\u00eda Jr.** (71.35) and **Josh Jung** (64.50) also present as strong starts; **Luis Garc\u00eda Jr.** benefits from a favorable matchup against Keller and a +14% boost from his platoon dynamic, while **Josh Jung** utilizes a hitter-friendly venue and a high-leverage opportunity against Springs to drive his efficiency well above the 60-point threshold.\n\nWe are navigating a few high-risk matchups today that necessitate lower expectations. **Luis Robert Jr.** (41.31) and **Andy Pages** (43.51) remain in the lineup despite marginal scores, as they are facing high-caliber arms in Yamamoto and McLean. **Kyle Tucker** (55.58) and **Jackson Merrill** (54.03) find themselves in similar territory; despite their pedigree, the negative SP skill variance against their respective matchups suppresses their upside. The most difficult personnel decision involved **Miguel Vargas** (54.25), who came closest to cracking the lineup. Ultimately, the optimizer prioritized the higher ceiling of **Brady House** (57.21) against Keller, as **Brady House**'s batting order spot and platoon advantage against a mid-tier starter provided a more stable path to production than the outcome-volatile path facing **Miguel Vargas** against the formidable McClanahan.\n\nOwners should exercise caution with the middle of our outfield and catching rotation. While **Liam Hicks** (59.93) is trending toward our \"Strong\" tier, the sheer volume of elite SPs on the docket today\u2014specifically the likes of Yamamoto, Woo, and McLean\u2014means we are prioritizing raw scoring efficiency over categorical depth. Keep a close eye on the late-breaking lineups f